\title{Chirped standing wave acceleration of ions with intense lasers}

\author{F. Mackenroth}
\email{felix.mackenroth@chalmers.se}
\affiliation{Department of Physics, Chalmers University of Technology, SE-41296 G\"oteborg, Sweden}

\author{A. Gonoskov}
\affiliation{Department of Physics, Chalmers University of Technology, SE-41296 G\"oteborg, Sweden}
\affiliation{Institute of Applied Physics, Russian Academy of Sciences, Nizhny Novgorod 603950, Russia}
\affiliation{Lobachevsky State University of Nizhni Novgorod, Nizhny Novgorod 603950, Russia}

\author{M. Marklund}
\affiliation{Department of Physics, Chalmers University of Technology, SE-41296 G\"oteborg, Sweden}

\date{\today}
\begin{abstract}
We propose a novel mechanism for ion acceleration based on the guided motion of electrons from a thin target. The electron motion is locked to the moving nodes of a standing wave formed by a chirped laser pulse reflected from a mirror behind the target. This provides a stable longitudinal field of charge separation, thus giving rise to \textit{chirped standing wave acceleration} (CSWA) of the residual ions of the layer. We demonstrate, both analytically and numerically, that quasi-monoenergetic ion beams with energies of the order 100 MeV are feasible for realistic pulse energies of $10$ J. Moreover, a scaling law for higher laser intensities and layer densities is presented, indicating stable GeV-level energy gains of dense ion bunches, for soon-to-be available laser intensities.
\end{abstract}

\pacs{41.75.Jv,52.38.Kd,52.59.-f}
\maketitle

\begin{figure}[htp]\centering
 \includegraphics[height=0.4\linewidth]{Figure1.eps}
 \caption{(color online) Conceptual design of the chirped standing wave acceleration setup.}
 \label{fig:Setup}
\end{figure}

The acceleration of charged particles by intense laser systems has become an important cornerstone of plasma physics research over the past decades \cite{Daido_etal_2012,Macchi_etal_2013,SSBulanov_etal_2008a}. In order to achieve this goal there exist several basic principal approaches, each featuring its own benefits and drawbacks \cite{Mackenroth_etal_2016}. Target Normal Sheath Acceleration (TNSA) \cite{Roth_etal_2002,Mora_2003,Cowan_etal_2004,Passoni_etal_2010}, as well as Coulomb explosion of clusters \cite{Ditmire_etal_1997} or specially designed targets \cite{Esirkepov_etal_2002,SSBulanov_etal_2008b}, makes use of the local plasma heating at the focal spot and the subsequent expansion of this plasma. The robustness of this process makes it experimentally very accessible, but it also produces one of its main drawbacks: the stage of heating deprives us largely of control of the energy transformation making it difficult to deliver the laser energy precisely to a certain range of ion energies. Despite the wide possibilities for modifying the laser pulse and the target, this inevitably results in a broad ion spectrum, a comparably low total efficiency and a rather unfavorable scaling law for the ion energy as a function of the laser pulse intensity \cite{Daido_etal_2012,Macchi_etal_2013}. Approaches like collisionless shock acceleration \cite{Silva_etal_2004,Haberberger_etal_2012} can provide monoenergetic ion bunches, however, typically involve many energy transformation steps resulting in a comparatively low total efficiency and small number of accelerated ions. The approaches of hole boring \cite{Schlegel_etal_2009}, light sail, or laser piston, \cite{Esirkepov_etal_2004,Bulanov_etal_2010,Henig_etal_2009,Kar_etal_2012} imply more direct and thus controllable energy transfer to ions, yielding higher efficiency as well as more promising spectral properties and scaling laws. However, the balance between the plasma fields and the light pressure introduces an interface susceptible to instabilities \cite{Khudik_etal_2014,Sgattoni_etal_2015,Palmer_etal_2012}, which unfortunately strongly limit the acceleration process and can even make it experimentally unfeasible at least for moderate intensities. 

In this Letter we propose a new basic approach, which in principle provides an opportunity to overcome the outlined obstacles. The approach relies on shifting electrons locked between the electric field antinodes of a standing wave in a controlled manner. This leads to the creation of a capacitor-like electric field due to charge separation between the shifted electrons and the parent ions, the latter being less affected by the ponderomotive force but still being dragged by the electron layer. The strength and power of a corresponding field configuration was demonstrated for radiation pressure driven light sails crossing through an underdense plasma region \cite{Ji_etal_2014}. As the process involves ponderomotive confinement of the electrons from both sides, the locking mechanism does not assume the presence of any interface that is susceptible to instabilities. The necessary control can be achieved by reflecting a chirped laser pulse from a mirror placed behind the layer. The gradual, well controlled change of the wavelength of the laser leads to a changing position of the electric field nodes. Consequently, the motion of the locked electrons can then be coordinated with the ion acceleration in the generated electric field of charge separation, making the ions follow the locked electrons for a long distance. In principle, this approach thus only relies on a tunable laser chirp and a large bandwidth, which has been demonstrated to be possibly over more than two octaves \cite{Goulielmakis_etal_2008}. These features can be summarized as \textit{chirped standing wave acceleration} (CSWA).

We model the incident laser field as a circularly polarized plane wave of electric field amplitude $E_0$ and angular frequency $\omega_0$ depending on space-time only via the invariant phase $\eta=t-x/c$ where $c$ is the speed of light and $x$ ($p$) is the coordinate (momentum) along the laser's propagation direction. Upon reflection from a mirror placed at $x=0$ the laser will form a standing wave $E_\text{tot}(t,x) = E(\eta) - E(\eta_+)$, where the subtraction ensures the boundary condition $E_\text{tot}(t,x=0) \equiv0$, and $\eta_+=t+x/c$. By placing a thin plasma layer of areal density $\sigma$ inside the nodes of this standing wave, the layer of electrons (mass and charge $m_e$ and $e$, respectively) will be trapped by the ponderomotive force $F_\text{pond} =- e^2\left<E_\text{tot}^2(t,x)\right>/2m_e\omega_0^2 $, where the brackets indicate a temporal average. The ions, on the other hand, are less affected by this force. In contrast, they experience the electron layer's electrostatic force which varies from $F_C=0$ to $F_C=4\pi e^2\sigma$, depending on the ions' position inside the layer. We use the average value

