Realizing that for a realistic pulse $\omega(\eta)\sim \omega_0$ (up to a factor of order unity) we see that for a relativistic field strength ($a_0\gg1$) the electron layer will be compressed by the action of the ponderomotive force to a thickness $\Delta x \sim \lambda_0/a_0\ll \lambda_0$. 

\begin{figure}[t]\centering
 \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{Figure2.eps}
 \caption{(color online) Results from 1D PIC simulations for a laser pulse energy $\varepsilon_0=20$ J, bandwidth $\Delta\omega_0=0.5\omega_0$, chirp $\mathcal{C}=-7$. The longitudinal $E_x$ (magenta) and transverse $E_y$ (green) field components are shown as functions of coordinate together with the distributions of electrons (blue) and protons (red) in the plane of coordinate $x$ and momentum $p_x$ at three times: before the layer starts transmitting the incident radiation (a), during the CSWA with a standing wave formed in the laser's reflection (c) or by a mode of radiation locked between the layer and the mirror (e). The corresponding proton spectra are shown in panels (b), (d) and (f).}
 \label{fig:PhaseSpace}
\end{figure}

By an analogous argument it can be shown that for any single particle separated further from the electron layer than twice the derived layer thickness, the laser's ponderomotive force dominates over the Coulomb attraction between the electron and ion layers, ensuring the stability of the suggested scheme throughout the whole duration of the laser pulse. Inserting the field model from Eq.~(\ref{Eq:ChirpedField}) into Eq.~(\ref{Eq:ModelMomentum})  we arrive the optimal momentum

